LINE.Text: Mental Health Awareness Week
Mindfulness
Mindfulness originated from a Buddhist meditation
technique, but the concept has since been adapted.
Studies have shown that mindfulness based stress
reduction (MBSR) leads to a 70% reduction in anxiety.
Almost three-quarters of GPs say they feel
patients would benefit from learning mindfulness.
Tips to be more mindful:
As soon as you wake up. take a few minutes
to become aware of your surroundings
- what you see, hear, touch and smell.

Throughout the day if you begin
to feel anxious take deep breaths
and relax your muscles, one by one.
Focus on one task at a time and
actively listen during conversations.
Statistics sourced from the Mental Health Foundation.
Many counsellors now offer mindfulness as part of their treatment.
To find out more, please search for "Counselling Directory mindfulness' on Google.
